If something isn't working as expected, use the guide below before disassembling anything.


🔴 Power Supply Won't Turn On
    Check these first:
        Make sure the Black Wire 2 and Green Wire 1 are properly soldered together, and the connection is fully covered with electrical tape
        Make sure no exposed wires are touching each other
        Try unplugging and replugging the 24-pin connector — this can act as a reset for the power supply
        Make sure the power supply switch on the back is flipped to the ON position
        If it still won't turn on: Double-check that the correct wires were soldered. Using the wrong wires is the most common cause of this issue.

🔴 Fan Won't Spin
    Check these first:
        Confirm Black Wire 1 is inserted into the far left slot of the fan adapter port
        Confirm Yellow Wire 1 is inserted into the slot directly next to Black Wire 1
        Make sure all lever nuts are fully closed, and the wires are secure inside them
        Check that no wires have come loose from their connectors
        If the fan still won't spin: Try reseating the wires in the lever nuts and verify you are using the correct yellow and black wires from the labeled set.

🔴 Peltier Is Not Getting Cold
    Check these first:
        Verify the red wire of the peltier is connected to a yellow (12V) wire and the black wire is connected to a black (ground) wire
        Try flipping the peltier over — if it was installed upside down, it will heat up instead of cooling down
        Make sure thermal paste is applied evenly with no gaps or clumps
        Check that the peltier is firmly pressed flat against the fan and the surface below it
        If it still isn't cooling: Re-test the peltier in isolation using the method from Step 13. If it doesn't reach below room temperature during the isolated test, the peltier may be faulty and should be replaced.

🔴 LEDs Won't Light Up
    Check these first:
        Confirm Yellow Wire 3 is connected to the positive connection and Black Wire 5 is connected to the negative connection
        Make sure the metal arms of the LED connector are fully seated on the copper pads of the strip
        Check that the connection is wrapped in electrical tape and no wires are shorting
        If using the soldering method: Check that the solder joints are solid and not just resting on top of the copper pads.


🔴 No Particle Tracks Visible
    This is the most common issue and usually has a simple fix. Work through these in order:
        Wait longer — it can take 5–10 minutes after turning on for the chamber to reach the right temperature and for vapor to form
        Check the alcohol — make sure you used exactly 0.5mL spread evenly across the chamois cloth. Too much or too little will prevent tracks from forming
        Check the isopropyl concentration — use 90% or higher. Lower concentrations contain too much water and won't vaporize correctly
        Check the petri dish seal — make sure the lid is sitting flat and flush on the dish so vapor isn't escaping
        Check the thermal paste — if the peltier isn't making solid contact with the petri dish, the chamber won't get cold enough. Remove the dish, scrape off the old paste, apply a fresh even layer, and reseat the dish
        Check your radioactive source — make sure it is placed inside the petri dish and not blocked by anything
        Still no tracks? Turn off the chamber, let it warm up completely, reapply thermal paste, re-add the alcohol, and restart. Most cases are resolved this way.

🔴 Mist Is Visible But No Clear Tracks
    The chamber may not be cold enough yet. Give it a few more minutes
    Try dimming or turning off nearby lights and shining a flashlight at a low angle across the petri dish to make tracks easier to see
    Make sure the bottom of the petri dish is painted black — without it, tracks are much harder to spot against a bright background
    Wipe the bottom of the petri dish with a damp cloth soaked in alcohol
